So far as we can ascertain the theo· logical views ol Democritus, he held first the existence of a divine sub· stance pervading the whole universe, consisting of special atoms of the most subtle constitution. this is the θεία οὐσία in Clem. Alex. Strom. V, ᾗ 88, p. 698 Pott, and the κόσμου ψυχή in Plutarch Plac. Phil. 1, 7. From this substance proceed not only the individual gods but also the souls of living beings, which by breathing constantly receive as nourishment par· ticles of this same substance which pervades the air. Arist. De Resp. c. 4. It is this substance doubtless which Cicero here means by principia mentis, and which above also c. 12, 29 he intends by natura quae imagines fundat.
